  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:1-2",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Leviticus 4:1-2",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". A general introduction like that in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 1:1-2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". From here to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " a new class of sacrifices are prescribed, the Sin-Offerings and Guilt-Offerings, and the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "occasions",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " on which they are to be brought are specified, while in chs. 1–3 nothing is said about ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "when",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the sacrifices are to be brought; their ceremonial only is regulated. The Sin-Offering is for sins committed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "unwittingly",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "through ignorance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " A.V.); for sins committed presumptuously (Heb. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "with an high hand",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 15:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the punishment is ‘that soul shall be cut off from among his people.’ The same distinction is drawn in Psalms 19 where ‘hidden (‘secret’ A.V.) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "faults",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:12",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 4:12",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") are contrasted with ‘presumptuous ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sins",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:13",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 4:13",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). After this general statement, the material and manner of the offering are prescribed for four different classes: (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the anointed priest (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:3-12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") the congregation (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:13-21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "c",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") a ruler (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:22-26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "d",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") any one of the common people (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:27-35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Cp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 15:22-29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "We may observe that the directions for disposal of the Sin-Offering, though very similar in all four cases, are not absolutely identical. In (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") some of the blood is to be put upon the horns of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "altar of incense",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " inside the tent of meeting; all the rest of the blood is to be poured out at the foot of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "altar of burnt offering",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " at the door of the tent of meeting; the fat is to be burnt upon the altar of Burnt-Offering; the whole bullock is to be burnt without the camp: in (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "c",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "d",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") some of the blood is to be put upon the horns of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "altar of burnt offering",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; all the rest is to be poured out at the foot of that altar; the fat is to be burnt upon the altar; there is no command given as to the remainder.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "We notice that on no occasion is the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "whole",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " burnt upon the altar, as in the case of the Burnt-Offering.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "THE SIN OFFERING (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 5:1-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). At the time of the Mosaic legislation, burnt offerings and meat offerings were already in existence, and had existed from the time of the Fall. A beginning, therefore, is made with them, and the regulations of the peace offerings naturally follow, because these sacrifices succeed in order to the burnt and meat offerings, and because sacrifices in some respects of the same nature as peace offerings had previously existed under a different name (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 10:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 24:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and see above notes on chapter 3). The sin and trespass offerings, therefore, are left to the last, though, owing to their meaning, they were always offered first of all, when sacrifices of all three kinds were made together. They are the means of ceremonially propitiating God when alienated from his people, or from any individual member of it, by sin, which they legally atone for. The need of expiation is implied and suggested by the offering of the blood, both in the burnt sacrifice and the peace offering (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 1:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). But this was not sufficient; there must be a special sacrifice to teach this great truth as its primary lesson. The sin offering typifies the sacrifice of our Lord JESUS CHRIST upon the cross, as the great Sin Offering for mankind, whereby the wrath of God was propitiated, and an expiation for the sins of man was wrought, bringing about reconciliation between God and man. Leviticus 4:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Expiatory Sacrifices. - The sacrifices treated of in ch. 1-3 are introduced by their names, as though already known, for the purpose of giving them a legal sanction. But in ch. 4 and 5 sacrifices are appointed for different offences, which receive their names for the first time from the objects to which they apply, i.e., from the sin, or the trespass, or debt to be expiated by them: viz., חטּאת sin, i.e., sin-offering (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.), and אשׁם debt, i.e., debt-offering (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 5:15-16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 5:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); - a clear proof that the sin and debt-offerings were introduced at the same time as the Mosaic law. The laws which follow are distinguished from the preceding ones by the new introductory formula in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:1-2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which is repeated in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 5:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This repetition proves that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 4:2-5:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " treats of the sin-offerings, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 5:14-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the trespass-offerings; and this is confirmed by the substance of the two series of laws. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]